videoTitle: American living in Japan @mattjhannan
commentText: I visit Japan about twice a year. It is a blast each time. The laid back enjoy life mentality is great while vacationing. Then I envisioned myself living there and honestly I realized it is not worth it. The society is great and safe but the pressure is immense and the social aspect is very dulled. The society encourages self reliance and social isolation. Things are expensive if you live there. Right now it seems cheap because the dollar is strong vs the yen. But if you live there entry level jobs pay $1500 yen per hour and which would be $15 dollars per hour but due to currently at 67% of a dollar, It be rough. The crazy part is everything doesnâ€™t care about the 67% so therefore you have to live basically a frugal life. Now obviously if you had a high paying job it be great but imo the social aspect would be the most challenging. There are other challenges as well but since that society is full of temptations on the daily, I would think it be hard for many folks. But like this video suggests if you want to live that lifestyle at a young age, do it. If you harm yourself, doing it young seems to make the most sense. But as an older person say 40+ it be rough.

commentText: Im one of the few that got out.  Took the job offer from my uncle when i was 17, worked there for a year and a half while going to night school, loved it at first.  The only issue is working with my uncle sucks, hes the type to put others down to make himself look good and can never be wrong.  It was the same with one of the old guys there, the young generations is so weak willed and never wants to do shit, all i had to hear everyday at lunch.  Started eating in my truck every day, talking a lot less, just putting earbuds and going to work, i liked the hanging with the other guys my age, we were all in the same boat somewhat but they were a couple years older so they werent completely relateable.  It got to the point of me dreading waking up and going to work, not because of hard it was, the 11 hour shift and then going to school for 3 or 4 hours, it wasnt the shoveling gravels for 9 hours straight at 103F outside, it was the fact i had to get up and deal with those assholes for hours.  I finally finished night school and put in my 2 weeks to get ready for college to get my bachelors to become a therapist, it was the great 2 months of my life being free from everything for once.  My college plan has since fell through since i had to leave to take care of my mom but im a lot happier than i was then.

commentText: As a technical writer who's performed in both the User Manual Writer and the Documentation Writer spaces for 35 years or so, a few words of advice:  *_1  If you're going to be hired for your writing skills, you'd better have some._*  I've known a lot of 'technical writers' that struggled to deliver a product at a 6th grade level, while most corporate or government technical writing is going to be at 12th grade level or up.  *_2  Don't expect AI to save you._*  Technical writing is typically very narrow in scope and since the content will likely be new, any LLM-trained AI is not going to be able to write your content for you.  *_3  In addition to crafting prose in the King's English, you'll also need familiarity with HTML, SGML, and XML._*  Familiarity with different graphics formats, and their advantages/disadvantages, is a MUST.  *_4  Lastly, as a technical writer, you're going to need technical background beyond being able to record a macro in Microsoft Word._*  I spent 22 years as a Navy Electronics Tech with over 8000 hours of technical training.  That was a good start.

commentText: Actuarial analyst:  strong mathematical ability doesn't even come close to the level of math needed.  Imagine you have 1,000 people in a room who say they have a very strong mathematical skill set.  Maybe 3 of them have enough to be an actuary.  I have a B.S. in electrical engineering emphasizing CPU design.  Never got into the field because I graduated during the high tech bubble burst (no jobs at any company, anywhere in the world).  I do data analysis in the insurance industry.  Decided to self-study for the actuary exams. commentText: I once got fired from my dishwasher job for trying to call off sick. Was working there for over a year, and it was my 1st time calling out. I even had a doctor's note that I was contagious, and not to work around food.  Edit- I've been getting a lot of people questioning if this was true, and it absolutely is. I agree, doesn't make sense at all to fire someone you've been praising for over a year as your best dish washer, and is currently your only dishwasher after the other guy retired, just for calling out for the very first time with a 103 degree fever and a doctor's note.  No, it's not illegal per se, because I live in a no fault state, but I did speak to a lawyer. He assured me I had a case, and that it was a guaranteed victory, but since I'd only just recently become full time, I hadn't made enough for the settlement to have been worth the lawyer fees. Even in no fault states, you can still sue if you're fired for discriminatory purposes, like being black, gay or sick. That's how these companies get away with it, because they know people aren't likely to spend thousands of dollars just to say they were right.

videoTitle: losing your job US vs France #france #usa #livingabroad #workersrights #corporatelife #french
commentText: In New Zealand, there is a dismissal process and a good reason must be given, otherwise the employer can be sued. Also, appropriate notice must be given, unless it's a case of serious misconduct. In any circumstance, the person losing their job is still entitled to any annual holidays etc. they are owed, in their final pay. Here, healthcare is not tied to your job either, as most medical things are covered by the government anyway, except about $60 for GP visits. If you're fired, you can get the job seekers allowance almost immediately, plus accommodation supplement to get you through. It's really sad that the US treats people this way, when they are so wealthy. I'm guessing it won't change any time soon, unless there's a mass push for it from the population.

videoTitle: losing your job US vs France #france #usa #livingabroad #workersrights #corporatelife #french
commentText: I've tried explaining to my parents over and over that tying healthcare to your employer stifles the job market. People will take a crappy job they hate simply because it has decent benefits. If we had proper healthcare people would be less scared about starting their own business because not only would they have their own healthcare so would any employee they hire, instead of small business owners having to calculate what type of insurance they can provide and all the insane costs that come with it. Also people would able to work at jobs that they love that can't provide insurance due to the costs. And if you are between jobs you don't have to panic and grab the first thing you can find so that you can have insurance.

commentText: Just so people here know :in France we got two main type of job contracts, CDI (Contracts with Undefined Duration) and CDD (Contracts with Defined Duration). While both have the same protection as shown by this short, CDD last for a certain time, usually a year, and can just be not renewed. Of course, we are always informed what type is offered and signed, so wecan prepare.

videoTitle: losing your job US vs France #france #usa #livingabroad #workersrights #corporatelife #french
commentText: I was let go at a job about 10 months ago.   I was supposed to give them 30 days notice, I was given notice the day they came in and told me.   Depending on which state you live in unemployment is not a given.   It took me 9 months to find another job.   Luckily I had some savings.   I did not get healthy insurance (Medicaid) until after 6 months of being unemployed.   It was a tedious process that took forever.   I was afraid to drive my car anywhere because of lack of insurance.   I had to get food from a food bank because my 20 year old son could not get a job.   So I was buying groceries for him.   I was also paying for his college tuition.    It was a hard and difficult time.   Oh and the job I did end up taking is only 1099 (contracted) work.  I had to take it.   The only salary position that would potentially be available to me would not have started until almost a year after my last job.   The U.S. needs better labor protections.

commentText: "Right to Work" states in the U.S. are exactly like this.  I worked at a college for 23 years, 18 full time with excellent evaluations.  The president called over 20 of us into one of the new auditoriums and told us that he wasn't going to renew our contracts for the next year. commentText: I used to be an HR Manager in the UK and dealt with many large-scale redundancy situations. The process is so watertight and clear, and the ultimate aim is to generally KEEP them in employment by finding something which fits them. America - 'you're laid off sorry bye'

commentText: At the 27:53 mark, during the inquiry into whether AI could be held responsible for a teenager's suicide, the individual in red promptly affirmed with such self-confidence that it was an isolated incident. He then immediately redirected the discussion from the gravity of a human life lost to the assertion, "If we do not prevail in the AI competition, another global power such as China will." This viewpoint is particularly concerning given a recent discussion I coincidentally observed on today's episode of the Megyn Kelly show. The program featured the teenager's parents, Matt and Maria Raine, and their attorney, Jay Edelson, who presented substantial evidence indicating that such incidents are not isolated. The episode explored the tragic circumstances surrounding their son, Adam Raine's suicide, alleging that ChatGPT incited the act. The discussion also addressed the inherent risks of the platform, the ongoing legal action against the company, Sam Altman's response to these events, the disturbing interaction between ChatGPT and Adam, and the parents' dedication to increasing awareness about the dangers associated with this technology.

videoTitle: So where do sailors sleep?ğŸ§ #usslexingtonmuseum #seacadets #youthprogram
commentText: My five brothers and I toured the Lex while it was docked in Pensacola in 1971. We were headed to Disney World and my mother wrote to the commander. Usually tours were for groups but because there were 8 of us we were a group! My older brother had just completed Air National Guard boot camp so I'm sure they thought it would be a potential recruiting opportunity. It was an extensive tour and we got to eat lunch with the sailors who treated us like special guests. A great memory, to this day tours of ships and submarines are my favorite tourist activity. I've done them all over the US and the world. I recently toured the USS Texas in drydock, got to walk under the ship. It was a thrill, and as a Houstonian I had been on the ship many times. If you are in the area they are doing topside tours now that it's back in the water.

commentText: Was lucky to be invited on 9 day Tiger Cruise aboard carrier USS Reagan from Pearl Harbor to San Diego in 2011.  Had a middle rack in the stern with the air wing.  The noise from the A/C and gentle rocking of the ship gave me the best sleep of my life.  Still have occasional reveries of the experience.  The rest of the onboard experience was wonderful, including two underway air show performances that did things you wouldn't see at a shore based air show (e.g., live bombing of targets at close range from the ship).

commentText: In the early 70's the rack were also the lockers.  On our ship the best rack was the center  because the top rack got hot from sun shining on the top deck  and the bottom had to be strapped up in morings so they could clean the deck of the birthing compartment.

videoTitle: So where do sailors sleep?ğŸ§ #usslexingtonmuseum #seacadets #youthprogram
commentText: Deployed on the Forrestal in 86. At first, I was in squadron berthing which was on the 03 level. Flight deck is 04 level. We slept right below the arresting cables. After about three or four days, you are so tired you eventually sleep through anything.   When I transferred to AIMD, my berthing was on the 01 level, forward of the hangar bay. Now the big noise was the steam catapults launching aircraft. After arresting cables, no problem.  Yes, with rack curtains and a functional rack light, my rack was my retreat. Because I worked on critical aircraft components, I did not have a general quarters station unless I was on shift. Most GQ drills happened during day check; I worked night check. I remember the quiet solitude during GQ drills.  Another fond memory of berthing compartments was during lights out hours was the red compartment lights. Very soothing.

commentText: Slovakia made this kind of stuff illegal. Every time a position becomes available or a new one is created, employers have to report it to the local ''job centre''. Employers can advertise open positions online or find employees through those job centres (they often get extra money from the state for employing unemployed people from job centres) but they can only advertise the actual open/new positions. They can't advertise something that does not exist. It falls under ''false advertising''. Another good thing is that they must state the salary in their adverts. I know it's a thing in some countries where employers advertise a job but they will only tell you what the salary is when you come to an interview.

commentText: There are two options for the future:  1. We accept that as technology becomes more autonomous, we need to work less and this will have more time for family, art, and life in general. 2. We allow wealth to concentrate as larger and larger portions of the population are deemed unnecessary and watch those on the edge of irrelevance work themselves to death for the ever shrinking minority living in extreme wealth.  There was a time not that long ago when people were beginning to work only 8 hours a day 5 days a week and they assumed that trend would continue as technology made us more productive. We should all ask ourselves why that didn't happen despite workers today being the most productive in history.

If you have a full-time job in America, even at minimum wage, you are easily in the global top 15% of incomes. Americans are 4.5% of the global population, but responsible for 36% of global consumption and 30% of waste. Even the bottom quarter of Americans by income consume more than double the global average.  It's difficult to reconcile these two ways of looking at inequality. Is 36% of global consumption not enough for Americans?   And how much more do you think you'd have if we took away all of the billionaires wealth and distributed it evenly? It turns out if you completely liquidated every nickel of wealth of all of Americans billionares, you could give every American a one-time payment of $20,000. But that's assuming you could liquidate at face value, which of course you can't. Trying to do that would decimate the stock market and destroy millions of people's retirement savings, and you could probably only extract about quarter of that. So woohoo, no more billionares! We all get ... $5000, once. Not medicare for all, not a glorious utopia. Just a one time payment of five grand.
